{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"bbad3974-aa4c-45a9-b2fc-860c0c6ab3af","content":"`SafeAreaEdges` isn't a built-in .NET MAUI property — it's likely being silently ignored. Here's what you actually need:\n\n**On iOS**, use the platform-specific API:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\">\n```\n\n**On Android (.NET 9+/API 35+)**, edge-to-edge is enforced by the OS, but MAUI still applies safe-area padding. Override it in your platform code (`Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`):\n\n```csharp\nprotected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n{\n    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n    // Tell the framework not to fit content inside system bars\n    WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window, false);\n}\n```\n\nYou'll need `using AndroidX.Core.View;`.\n\n**Also ensure:**\n1. **No implicit chrome** — if your page is inside a `Shell` or `NavigationPage`, hide the nav bar:\n   ```xml\n   Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"\n   ```\n2. **Image fills the space** — use `Aspect=\"AspectFill\"` with fill layout options:\n   ```xml\n   <Image Source=\"photo.jpg\"\n          Aspect=\"AspectFill\"\n          HorizontalOptions=\"Fill\"\n          VerticalOptions=\"Fill\" />\n   ```\n3. **No page-level Padding** — confirm `Padding=\"0\"` on the `ContentPage`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e6e1c91b-ff54-40ce-8232-72b67e29789e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making content go edge-to-edge in a .NET MAUI app, going behind the status bar and navigation bar. They've tried `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage but the image still has padding.\n\nThis is a common .NET MAUI question. Let me think about what they need:\n\nIn .NET MAUI, to achieve true edge-to-edge content that goes behind system bars, you typically need to:\n\n1. Set the page to ignore safe areas (which they've done with `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` - though the actual API might be different)\n2. On Android, you need to enable edge-to-edge mode\n\n\n3. On iOS, I need to verify the correct platform-specific property — it's likely `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` rather than the generic `SafeAreaEdges` property they mentioned, since that might not be the actual MAUI API available in their version.\n\nFor Android, edge-to-edge support depends on the .NET MAUI version and target API level, so I should clarify what approach works for their specific setup. default. But .NET MAUI might still add padding for safe areas.\n\nThe key things the user likely needs:\n\n1. **Remove the NavigationPage shell** - If the page is wrapped in a NavigationPage or Shell, there's a navigation bar taking space\n2. **iOS safe area** - Use `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"`  \n3. **Android** - May need to configure the window to draw behind system bars\n4. **Image Aspect** - Set `Aspect=\"AspectFill\"` on the Image to fill the space\n\nActually, for .NET 10 (which the user mentions), let me think about what APIs exist. .NET 10 is the next version after .NET 9. \n\nThe property `SafeAreaEdges` is not a standard .NET MAUI property I'm aware of. The user might be confusing it with something else.\n\nFor the solution, I need to disable the iOS safe area with the platform-specific namespace and property, handle Android's edge-to-edge behavior which is default on Android 15+, strip away any Shell or NavigationPage wrappers, and configure the Image to fill the entire page with `AspectFill`.","outputTokens":1476,"requestId":"9BD7:35BDDE:607D50B:6BC8AD4:69EC1103"},"id":"98173c1d-905f-49f8-9ab5-040afa7a7f48","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:56:00.769Z","parentId":"2fc18cde-0807-47dc-8799-a5b4959c4a73"}
